South Africa Stocks Rise for First Day in Five, Led by AngloGold and Sasol

-- B y   S i k o n a t h i   M a n t s h a n t s h a   a n d   C a r l i   L o u r e n s
-- 
2011-02-21T16:32:57Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-02-21/south-africa-stocks-rise-for-first-day-in-five-eqstra-lonmin-mondi-move.html
South Africa’s FTSE/JSE  Africa  All
Share Index climbed for the first in five days, adding 292.64,
or 0.9 percent, to 32,806.67 at the 5 p.m. close in
Johannesburg.  The following were among the most active stocks in the
South African market today.    AngloGold Ashanti Ltd . (ANG SJ), the world’s third-largest
gold producer, climbed by the most in more than three months,
gaining 11.74 rand, or 3.5 percent, to 351.74 rand. Gold rose to
a seven-week high in  London .  Gold Fields Ltd . (GFI SJ), Africa’s
second-largest producer, jumped 3.8 percent to 128.40 rand and
Harmony Gold Mining Co. (HAR SJ), the continent’s third-largest
producer, rallied 6.3 percent, its biggest increase in more than
a year, to 84.49 rand.    Eqstra Holdings Ltd . (EQS SJ), an industrial and heavy
equipment rental company, gained the most since Aug. 31,
climbing 33 cents, or 5.2 percent, to 6.63 rand. The company
posted first-half net income of 128 million rand ($18 million)
compared with a loss of 58 million rand a year earlier.    Famous Brands Ltd . (FBR SJ), an fast-food chain holdings
company, had its biggest gain in almost four months. The stock
rose 1.72 rand, or 4.5 percent, to 39.82 rand. The company
acquired Milky Lane and Juicy Lucy from Java Brands for 31
million rand.    Mondi Plc  (MND SJ),  Europe ’s largest maker of office paper,
snapped three days of losses, advancing 1.35 rand, or 2.2
percent, to 62.95 rand. The company said today net income was
224 million euros ($307 million), or 43.6 cents a share,
compared with a loss of 33 million euros, or 6.5 cents, a year
earlier.  SacOil Holdings Ltd. (SCL SJ), the African oil explorer,
rose the most in almost two weeks, gaining 9 cents, or 4.9
percent, to 1.94 rand. Public Investment Corp., which manages
the South African government’s pension funds, will take a 7.44
percent stake in the company for about 1.50 rand a share, SacOil
said.    Sasol Ltd . (SOL SJ), the world’s biggest maker of motor
fuel from coal, climbed the most since Feb. 11, rising 10.33
rand, or 2.8 percent, to 374.83 rand. Crude rose as much as 5.2
percent to $94.36 a barrel in New York trading as anti-
government protests continued in  Libya , holder of the largest
crude oil reserves on the African continent, and in other oil-
producing parts of the region. Violence has also flared in
Yemen, Djibouti and Bahrain as governments sought to crack down
on demonstrations.  Telkom South Africa Ltd. (TKG SJ), Africa’s biggest fixed-
line operator, gained the most in eight months, jumping 1.19
rand, or 3.4 percent, to 36.49 rand. The company may name Romeo Kumalo, an executive at Vodacom Group Ltd., as chief executive
officer, the  Sunday Times  reported, without saying where it got
the information.  Truworths International Holdings Ltd. (TRU SJ),  South
Africa ’s largest clothing retailer, gained 1.29 rand, or 2
percent, to 66.79 rand, the most since Feb. 17. Net income
increased 19 percent to 1.03 billion rand. The company said it
will consider share buy-backs and potential investment and
acquisition opportunities.  Woolworths Holdings Ltd. (WHL SJ), a South African food and
clothing retailer, climbed for a third day, jumping 85 cents, or
3.3 percent, to 26.45 rand. Investec Ltd.’s securities unit
raised its recommendation on the stock to “buy” from “hold”
and increased its price estimate to 31.60 rand. Citigroup Inc.
lifted its price estimate to 33 rand from 29 rand.  To contact the reporter on this story:
